						<li class="Comment FLC Comment-Parent" comment_id="580994" content_type="article" content_id="15748">
	<footer class="meta">
		<a href="http://www.cracked.com/members/AMerriwether/" class="user">
		AMerriwether			<img src="http://i-beta.crackedcdn.com/phpimages/members/avatars/3/1/164853_45.jpg?1" alt="" class="avatar"/>
		</a>

		<p class="date">Posted on <time datetime="2010-10-29T19:14:09-07:00">10/29/2010 07:14 PM</time>
		</p>
	</footer>
	<p class="text">Immersion is bulls**t.  Video games are games, not virtual reality.  Analogy: a basketball court made of pure ebony is no better for playing basketball than a basketball court made of well-kept asphalt.  They both serve the purpose of the game mechanics.  Hell, even a grass court is fun to play onI did it enough.<br />
<br />
I think that many of these problemsthe inability to jump over small obstacles, for exampleare created by the unimportant aspects of the games, the veneer that the developers put on them.  In essence, because you're playing as a humanoid being, an inability to jump makes the character seem crippled.  This is why games like Baldur's Gate allow the players to jump, even though jumping adds literally nothing to the game: there are no obstacles overcome by jumping, no jumping attacks, jumping does not help you avoid enemiesbut if you couldn't jump you'd be a cripple, not a hero.<br />
<br />
On the other hand, abstract games that focus on gameplay more than the veneer do not raise these issues.  As Mario in Super Mario Bros., it does not bother anyone that you can swim underwater indefinitely in some levels, while in other levels you die instantly if you fall into it as if it were lava.  It doesn't bother anyone that you're working your ass off to save a kingdom that seems to have all of ten non-evil inhabitants (assuming Mario lives there).  It doesn't bother anyone that, despite being a plumber, Mario has never, in his history in video games (not TV, don't go there) PLUNGED ANYTHING.<br />
<br />
Immersion makes for a great story, but it ruins games.  Immersion needs to be ended.  Preferably violently.</p>

		
	
	
	
